      },
      "date": "2011-04-30 20:05:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI am discussing with jay whether it makes sense to hold the inode through cl_page, since it will make things simpler. So I just temporarily gave - for this patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "26ceaf44e420d27da98c3542a92f8dfbd0b4cab3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-03 04:02:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nTo wangdi: I've thought about your proposal, there are two difficulties to hold an inode refcount for each page:\n1. the overhead of grabbing an inode refcount is not trivial. From the implementation of igrab(), it has to hold a global spinlock inode_lock, this would make it super busy;\n2. The race between clear_inode() and cl_lock_page_out(). This is a livelock case where the former is called when the final inode refcount is dropped(we may do this inside cl_page_put()), then clear_inode will clear cl_object by waiting for the object refcount to reach zero. However, the same process is actually hold the cl_lock to call cl_lock_page_out(). We may make extra effort to fix this problem.\n\n\nAnyway, I realize this patch is too long to be inspected. I should have split the patch into multiple parts.\n\nLet's see Wally's test on a system with less memory, with the patch of ll_delete_inode(). If we can survive, maybe we can drop this and use ll_delete_inode() solution, though it's a workaround one.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
